1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:00,712
We can begin.

2
00:00:02,535 --> 00:00:19,760
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa

3
00:00:20,347 --> 00:00:33,667
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

4
00:00:36,612 --> 00:00:40,078
So the title of this is Death.

5
00:00:41,493 --> 00:00:42,356
A happy subject.

6
00:00:43,139 --> 00:00:46,954
I've started off here with a quote from St. Paul's letter to the Corinthians.

7
00:00:47,676 --> 00:00:49,323
O death, where is thy sting?

8
00:00:49,444 --> 00:00:51,773
O grave, where is thy victory?

9
00:00:52,866 --> 00:00:56,213
Now, it also reminds me, of course, of my Roman Catholic upbringing.

10
00:00:56,734 --> 00:01:01,161
Now, in that doctrine, there are three realms.

11
00:01:01,661 --> 00:01:03,564
There's hell, from which you never escape.

12
00:01:03,765 --> 00:01:05,248
That's bad news, isn't it?

13
00:01:05,268 --> 00:01:07,352
And there's heaven, from which you never want to escape.

14
00:01:07,871 --> 00:01:11,718
But there's this little sort of in-between place called purgatory.

15
00:01:11,698 --> 00:01:17,608
Now it's because, you know, most of us don't die with terrible sins on our hearts.

16
00:01:18,468 --> 00:01:25,840
We just need a little place where we get smacked about a bit and then we're ready to move up into the heavenly realms.

17
00:01:25,921 --> 00:01:35,174
Now whether these realms actually exist or not, as you can say for any of these religions with their realms, the Buddhists have hundreds of them,

18
00:01:36,504 --> 00:01:40,129
The fact is they do mirror our mental states.

19
00:01:40,870 --> 00:01:55,849
So hell, of course, are those times in our lives when, you know, things fall apart, everything's going wrong, we lose our work, everything looks really sort of bad, especially, for instance, people who are suffering from this COVID business.

20
00:01:57,230 --> 00:02:02,257
And heaven are those wonderful little moments when really, you know, this is the life.

21
00:02:02,496 --> 00:02:02,998
You know what I mean?

22
00:02:03,018 --> 00:02:04,959
We're out there and we're really enjoying it.

23
00:02:06,120 --> 00:02:16,248
But most of our time, or at least it's true for me, is that sort of in-between place of purgatory, where I'm not so happy and I'm not so sad.

24
00:02:17,409 --> 00:02:27,262
So the reason I mention this is because in the Catholic religion, the Roman Catholic religion, November is a special time.

25
00:02:27,342 --> 00:02:28,263
It's a funny month.

26
00:02:28,683 --> 00:02:34,211
It doesn't have the colour of October and it doesn't have the promise of December.

27
00:02:34,670 --> 00:02:37,814
It's a sort of dowdy month, dank.

28
00:02:37,794 --> 00:03:03,381
getting darker and this was a month that was dedicated to the holy souls so these were the people who'd ended up in purgatory and who um would eventually rise to heavenly uh heavenly uh joy and our we could help them by praying for them uh and that were little shots of grace and would help them to generate the energy they needed and so on and so forth

29
00:03:04,002 --> 00:03:13,489
So it occurred to me that this would be a wonderful full moon dedicated to the contemplation of death.

30
00:03:14,379 --> 00:03:17,683
Now, I know you're very excited by this, I'm sure of it.

31
00:03:18,305 --> 00:03:26,854
So, if we now consider that actually death is right with us at every moment, at the beginning of time.

32
00:03:26,914 --> 00:03:34,484
Now, when we say the beginning of time, we're not talking about historical time, we're talking about this moment arising and passing away.

33
00:03:34,985 --> 00:03:36,947
What is arising and passing away?

34
00:03:37,407 --> 00:03:38,588
Moments of consciousness.

35
00:03:39,030 --> 00:03:44,015
Each moment of consciousness has a moment of initial delusion.

36
00:03:43,996 --> 00:03:47,300
And then it finishes and that delusion finishes.

37
00:03:47,841 --> 00:03:51,125
That essential delusion, of course, is to do with identity.

38
00:03:51,444 --> 00:03:59,034
And here is the corner, here is the basic reason for our fear, our terror of death.

39
00:04:00,556 --> 00:04:02,739
And therein lies the destruction of that fear.

40
00:04:03,400 --> 00:04:05,042
Now here's what the Buddha says.

41
00:04:05,224 --> 00:04:34,523
he tells us about contemplation which he says is the most powerful of all contemplations because it reaches down to that very foundation stone of delusion the self-identity there's one thing the self doesn't want to do is die this is what he says monks mindfulness of death when developed and pursued is of great fruit and great benefit it gains a footing in nirvana the deathless

42
00:04:35,110 --> 00:04:38,754
Has Nibbāna, the deathless, has its final end?

43
00:04:41,656 --> 00:04:42,658
Now, what's he saying there?

44
00:04:42,718 --> 00:04:48,204
He's saying that if we contemplate death, we'll have a glimpse of Nibbāna.

45
00:04:48,363 --> 00:04:49,925
That's the footing, a glimpse of it.

46
00:04:50,425 --> 00:05:03,480
And if we continue to contemplate our deaths, it'll actually lead us to the end of death, to the experience of that which doesn't die, the deathless, the amatādhamma, the deathless truth.

47
00:05:05,232 --> 00:05:11,961
Now, I like to quote Franz Becker, who wrote this wonderful book called The Denial of Death.

48
00:05:12,060 --> 00:05:13,142
It's still a smashing read.

49
00:05:13,704 --> 00:05:14,665
He wrote it in 1973.

50
00:05:15,146 --> 00:05:17,007
He got the Pulitzer Prize for this something.

51
00:05:17,369 --> 00:05:19,851
But there's a line in that which captures it all.

52
00:05:20,372 --> 00:05:34,091
The basic motivation for human behavior is our biological need to control our basic anxiety, to deny the terror of death.

53
00:05:34,797 --> 00:05:37,360
Now, we've seen this with COVID, right?

54
00:05:37,439 --> 00:05:44,607
The enormous terror, the fear, people locking themselves away, wearing masks, doing all sorts.

55
00:05:44,627 --> 00:05:46,629
And of course, there was a certain reason for that.

56
00:05:46,689 --> 00:05:48,029
People were actually dying.

57
00:05:48,069 --> 00:05:52,615
But for most people who got COVID, it was just a very nasty type of flu.

58
00:05:53,115 --> 00:06:04,146
But even so, this basic motivation for human behavior, it sits right there underneath everything, this fear that we're going to die at any moment.

59
00:06:04,125 --> 00:06:06,588
Dying on the in-breath, dying on the out-breath.

60
00:06:08,810 --> 00:06:13,355
And that's why he says, you know, that's why the Buddha points to it as the most powerful.

61
00:06:13,716 --> 00:06:17,521
This is the only contemplation where he says you can actually experience nibbana.

62
00:06:17,880 --> 00:06:26,329
So you can throw away all this vipassana stuff and all that, metta and all that, just sit there from now on contemplating death and you'll make it.

63
00:06:26,850 --> 00:06:28,733
That's how powerful it is.

64
00:06:29,725 --> 00:06:32,588
Now this is now, how often should we contemplate death?

65
00:06:32,608 --> 00:06:35,571
So here's the Buddha asking the question.

66
00:06:35,992 --> 00:06:37,473
So this is a paraphrase.

67
00:06:37,913 --> 00:06:41,637
So the Buddha asked several monks, how often do you contemplate death?

68
00:06:42,199 --> 00:06:45,141
And one of them replied, Lord, I contemplate death every day.

69
00:06:45,742 --> 00:06:49,487
Not good enough day, the Lord wasn't happy with that.

70
00:06:49,507 --> 00:06:55,072
Then he asked another one and he said, well, I contemplate death with every mouthful I take at a meal.

71
00:06:55,793 --> 00:06:57,235
Not good enough, said the Buddha.

72
00:06:57,603 --> 00:06:59,925
And then he turns to another and he says, what about you?

73
00:06:59,946 --> 00:07:05,113
And he says, well, I contemplate death with each in-breath and out-breath.

74
00:07:05,134 --> 00:07:06,776
Ah, now the Buddha was pleased, you see.

75
00:07:07,276 --> 00:07:09,160
In other words, you do it all the time.

76
00:07:09,600 --> 00:07:12,043
Now, you can't actually do it all the time.

77
00:07:12,264 --> 00:07:14,586
You can't be thinking about death while you're adding up your bills.

78
00:07:14,607 --> 00:07:15,267
It would be awful.

79
00:07:16,029 --> 00:07:19,875
It's more in the sense of it's always there as a background.

80
00:07:19,954 --> 00:07:23,339
It's always there sitting on your shoulder.

81
00:07:23,319 --> 00:07:38,187
And as you know, in medieval times, it was quite regular to have a memento mori, a reminder of death on your desk, on your shelf, by your bedside, just somewhere where the eye would catch it every so often.

82
00:07:38,728 --> 00:07:42,595
And it would just remind you, you know, OK, in the end, there is death.

83
00:07:45,341 --> 00:08:06,422
of course if uh if we constantly ignore that if we constantly ignore death distract ourselves from it then it'll just take us by surprise i mean i have this terrible fear that i will be holding a piece of toast just dripping with with margarine and layered with great big

84
00:08:07,701 --> 00:08:29,658
topping of of marmalade and holding it to my holding it up like this so i can see it and i can begin to begin to sit to to enjoy this lovely aroma and suddenly i get a heart attack see now what am i going to do am i going to am i going to actually make the effort to take that one last bite or will i be able to just drop the whole damn toast who knows

85
00:08:31,444 --> 00:08:47,480
So now there is a lovely example from the Zen tradition where a monk flips over or falls over a cliff and he's hanging there by his fingernails, but he has time to admire, peeping from a cranny, this wonderful golden flower.

86
00:08:49,543 --> 00:08:52,466
So the Buddha also talks about these four types of people.

87
00:08:52,505 --> 00:08:57,991
He says there are people who wake up, that's how he puts it, as soon as they hear even the word of death.

88
00:08:58,360 --> 00:09:04,455
Then there are those who don't wake up until somebody close, your mother, your father, somebody dies who is close to you.

89
00:09:04,687 --> 00:09:07,572
There are those who don't wake up until lots of people have died.

90
00:09:07,672 --> 00:09:14,822
So I think, you know, all these deaths caused by COVID have had some effect, especially on young people.

91
00:09:14,922 --> 00:09:19,609
We seem to be getting a lot of 20 to 20, 30 year olds coming to meditate.

92
00:09:20,190 --> 00:09:21,892
There's a sort of an awakening, you know?

93
00:09:22,312 --> 00:09:28,541
And then of course the most unfortunate is to wake up to death when the doctor tells you you've got six weeks.

94
00:09:30,264 --> 00:09:31,205
You definitely don't want that.

95
00:09:31,245 --> 00:09:33,327
That is definitely a terminal shock.

96
00:09:36,532 --> 00:09:42,144
So our work, Ben, is really to get ready.

97
00:09:42,205 --> 00:09:47,557
And you could say that every time you meditate, you are actually preparing yourself for your death.

98
00:09:47,857 --> 00:09:55,434
So without any further ado, we can do these contemplations.

99
00:09:56,072 --> 00:09:58,395
Contemplation is not thinking about it.

100
00:09:58,596 --> 00:10:01,458
So we're not sitting there saying, death, I wonder what it means.

101
00:10:01,519 --> 00:10:02,159
Where will I go?

102
00:10:02,200 --> 00:10:04,964
I wonder where I'll be reborn or something like that.

103
00:10:05,264 --> 00:10:06,225
No, it's nothing to do with that.

104
00:10:06,745 --> 00:10:12,351
It's to do with getting down to our relationship with death, which is always in the heart, right?

105
00:10:12,371 --> 00:10:17,018
The fear, the terror, the aversion, it's always down here in the heart somewhere.

106
00:10:19,360 --> 00:10:24,706
So what we do is we repeat these phrases slowly, right?

107
00:10:25,586 --> 00:10:32,875
And we're centering in on the heart and we're noticing any aversion, any pushing away, any fear, anything at all.

108
00:10:33,635 --> 00:10:37,259
And we're just waiting for that to begin to dissolve, right?

109
00:10:37,340 --> 00:10:38,041
Begin to dissolve.

110
00:10:38,380 --> 00:10:43,908
And if you keep saying it, you see, you keep saying it, you know, this body is subject to death.

111
00:10:44,107 --> 00:10:45,730
This body is subject.

112
00:10:46,009 --> 00:10:47,150
And play with it.

113
00:10:47,611 --> 00:10:48,793
This body.

114
00:10:48,875 --> 00:10:50,097
is subject to death.

115
00:10:51,240 --> 00:10:54,328
This body is subject to death.

116
00:10:55,511 --> 00:10:59,442
This body is subject to death.

117
00:10:59,590 --> 00:11:06,076
So you play around with it and very slowly you just get that feeling of surrender, surrendering to the truth.

118
00:11:06,797 --> 00:11:13,243
And that resistance vanishes and with it there comes that lovely sense of relief and then even a smile.

119
00:11:13,964 --> 00:11:19,528
You can even sort of laugh because you've suddenly realised that there is no monster under the bed.

120
00:11:19,610 --> 00:11:21,211
It's not something to be afraid of.

121
00:11:21,311 --> 00:11:26,735
It's just something that's going to happen anyway.

122
00:11:26,836 --> 00:11:28,298
So,

123
00:11:29,729 --> 00:11:34,013
That's the important thing about mantra, about contemplation practice, right?

124
00:11:34,033 --> 00:11:38,297
Those of you who've done mantra, those who've done contemplative prayer will understand that.

125
00:11:39,678 --> 00:11:42,081
But others won't have done this really.

126
00:11:43,682 --> 00:11:53,591
So, I mean, we're going to do very regular ones, but eventually you can find a phrase, you can find a passage in a book, and you just keep reading it.

127
00:11:53,631 --> 00:11:58,976
You don't think about it, you just keep reading it to get the feel of it, how you're relating to it.

128
00:12:01,032 --> 00:12:14,654
Okay, so here we go, and we're going to do the three of the messengers from the gods that awoke the Buddha to his path.

129
00:12:14,674 --> 00:12:18,500
Of course, this is a mythical way of what actually happened to him

130
00:12:18,480 --> 00:12:44,590
as a young man right so he's out he's been brought up in this luxurious palace he goes out he sees for the first time somebody who's terribly ill a very old person and a corpse but he also sees somebody sitting under a tree an ascetic under a tree which gives him the hope that in fact there's an escape from sickness aging and death so that's what we're going to do we're just going to repeat these to ourselves so okay so make sure you feel settled

131
00:12:46,696 --> 00:12:49,940
So sickness is a mini-death, it's a preparation for death.

132
00:12:51,120 --> 00:12:53,364
The body manifests its vulnerability.

133
00:12:54,544 --> 00:12:58,889
There's discomfort or pain, and there's some disability.

134
00:13:01,033 --> 00:13:04,557
This contemplation undermines our intoxication with youth.

135
00:13:04,616 --> 00:13:05,477
This is the Buddha.

136
00:13:05,957 --> 00:13:14,187
It undermines our intoxication with staying young, to always being 60 than you're 40, always being 30.

137
00:13:16,024 --> 00:13:19,111
So sickness is unpreventable.

138
00:13:21,638 --> 00:13:27,451
Just repeating gently into our hearts, this body is subject to disease.

139
00:13:45,522 --> 00:13:49,591
This body is of a nature to fall ill.

140
00:14:18,951 --> 00:14:22,498
This body has not gone beyond sickness.

141
00:14:53,157 --> 00:14:55,340
Aging is a progressive dying.

142
00:14:57,302 --> 00:15:09,337
Contemplating aging undermines the obsession with health and beauty, with intolerances, with fasting, food ingredients and all that other stuff.

143
00:15:09,357 --> 00:15:11,640
Aging is inevitable.

144
00:15:14,865 --> 00:15:21,914
Just repeating into our hearts, this body is subject to aging.

145
00:15:49,434 --> 00:15:53,067
This body has not gone beyond aging.

146
00:16:22,426 --> 00:16:25,855
This body is now in a process of aging.

147
00:16:52,514 --> 00:16:59,826
Some quotes from the Buddha, taken from parts of the scriptures and the Dhammapada.

148
00:16:59,846 --> 00:17:01,289
Life is uncertain.

149
00:17:01,350 --> 00:17:04,756
Death is certain.

150
00:17:07,882 --> 00:17:16,917
It undermines the overwhelming clinging to life at all costs, to shoring it up, barricading it with fame, riches and power.

151
00:17:21,808 --> 00:17:23,911
Death is inescapable.

152
00:17:25,712 --> 00:17:26,933
Everyone must die.

153
00:17:26,973 --> 00:17:33,920
The remainder of our lifespan is decreasing continually.

154
00:17:37,323 --> 00:17:43,269
Death will come regardless of whether or not we have made time to practice Dharma.

155
00:17:47,132 --> 00:17:49,875
We don't know when we are going to die.

156
00:17:53,112 --> 00:17:56,255
Human life expectancy is uncertain.

157
00:17:58,977 --> 00:18:00,818
There are many causes of death.

158
00:18:03,561 --> 00:18:05,784
The body is very fragile.

159
00:18:09,267 --> 00:18:15,471
Only the practice of Dharma can help us at the time of death.

160
00:18:15,491 --> 00:18:17,013
Our wealth cannot help us.

161
00:18:19,276 --> 00:18:21,718
Our loved ones cannot help us.

162
00:18:23,740 --> 00:18:26,807
Our body cannot help us.

163
00:18:30,015 --> 00:18:32,160
Death is inescapable.

164
00:18:34,566 --> 00:18:37,372
Repeating gently into the heart.

165
00:18:40,018 --> 00:18:42,423
This body is subject to death.

166
00:19:03,041 --> 00:19:06,144
This body has not gone beyond death.

167
00:19:30,066 --> 00:19:32,188
This body will die.

168
00:19:52,942 --> 00:19:56,586
Now usually tagged onto that are the contemplations about karma.

169
00:19:57,929 --> 00:19:59,371
I own my actions.

170
00:19:59,951 --> 00:20:02,674
I inherit the results of my actions.

171
00:20:03,717 --> 00:20:05,960
I am born of my actions.

172
00:20:06,621 --> 00:20:08,644
I'm related through my actions.

173
00:20:09,585 --> 00:20:12,028
I live dependent on my actions.

174
00:20:12,749 --> 00:20:17,336
And whatever I do, for good or for ill, I shall inherit the results.

175
00:20:18,436 --> 00:20:21,260
So that's something we can always add on.

176
00:20:23,384 --> 00:20:36,876
So now, if we get into that practice just for, you know, every morning, it's just a little reminder, it can be just half a minute, it can be five minutes, it doesn't really matter.

177
00:20:37,917 --> 00:20:40,861
And it has that effect on our lives.

178
00:20:41,621 --> 00:20:47,586
Okay, the first one is that sense of relief that comes with the acceptance of the inevitable.

179
00:20:48,268 --> 00:20:49,729
We simply stop fighting.

180
00:20:50,958 --> 00:20:58,528
There's so much energy pushing away those thoughts about death, about falling ill, about COVID, and that energy is all released.

181
00:21:00,049 --> 00:21:05,297
The underlying fear of sickness, aging and death, it puts a pall over our lives.

182
00:21:05,817 --> 00:21:08,800
Now you can see life is much more colorful.

183
00:21:09,061 --> 00:21:10,262
We appreciate it more.

184
00:21:11,003 --> 00:21:16,932
We regain some of that childlike wonder, the miracle of life, being conscious.

185
00:21:18,278 --> 00:21:30,631
Now with that there comes a sense of gratitude and of course with gratitude always the desire to share our joys and to comfort others in their sorrow.

186
00:21:30,651 --> 00:21:36,336
Accepting death as part of life cycle, it's much more easy to be with people who are sick.

187
00:21:37,218 --> 00:21:42,083
There's a much easier compassion for them and it's so much easier to see somebody who is dying.

188
00:21:43,104 --> 00:21:46,647
They don't represent for us something that we are afraid of anymore.

189
00:21:48,755 --> 00:21:52,318
The big thing about it too is that it does bring us into the present.

190
00:21:52,960 --> 00:22:04,574
If you've had a shock like you've fallen off a ladder or you've nearly missed being run over, then that really brings you into the present moment, the arising and passing away of every present moment.

191
00:22:05,414 --> 00:22:15,468
And it's within that moment that there may come just a glimpse or a realization of what is not changing, not conditioned.

192
00:22:15,968 --> 00:22:18,171
That is the beatitude of nibbana.

193
00:22:19,602 --> 00:22:24,328
And of course, that's why we practice Vipassana to keep us in touch with this impermanence.

194
00:22:25,309 --> 00:22:30,538
And when we're in touch with impermanence, we can see that holding on to anything is going to be illusory.

195
00:22:30,557 --> 00:22:34,103
It's bound to cause dissatisfaction because it disappears.

196
00:22:35,023 --> 00:22:43,355
And it also leads us to understand that anything we feel is substantial, that it has some sort of base of permanency, the sense of self.

197
00:22:43,435 --> 00:22:44,336
It can't be real.

198
00:22:45,178 --> 00:22:47,060
It's an illusion, a delusion.

199
00:22:49,150 --> 00:22:52,644
So that's the sort of benefits that we can get from it.

200
00:22:53,045 --> 00:22:57,522
And by practicing it as a constant,

201
00:22:58,246 --> 00:23:02,231
It eventually has an effect on us, just like practicing metta has an effect on us.

202
00:23:02,612 --> 00:23:10,384
But it's this constant practice, just a little moment every day, just after the vipassana, before the vipassana, it doesn't really matter.

203
00:23:11,065 --> 00:23:19,938
But just that constant little reminder, you see, and it just brings a spice into our life, which is, of course, very strange.

204
00:23:20,218 --> 00:23:22,801
You'd think the opposite, you'd think you'd become depressed.

205
00:23:24,772 --> 00:23:41,919
Anyway, I'd like to finish this little talk with a clip, which I think says everything, and which is expressed beautifully by Samuel Beckett.

206
00:23:42,299 --> 00:23:44,423
We are born astride a grave.

207
00:23:45,084 --> 00:23:49,671
It's not a very good clip, but I think the message gets across very clearly.

208
00:23:50,031 --> 00:23:50,932
So here we go.

209
00:24:01,307 --> 00:24:06,001
AHHHHHHHHH!

